description:
The HmassP_INPUTS timing profile (PR #2941) currently times SVDSBTL via a manual update-loop fallback because SVDSBTL inherits the default AbstractState::fast_evaluate that throws NotImplementedError. As a result, SVDSBTL pays the per-call AbstractState cache-flag bookkeeping (clear cached_*, set _phase, set _T/_p, etc.) on every probe in the batch, while IF97 — which DOES implement fast_evaluate — bypasses all of that.

On Ian's machine (2026-05-21):
  IF97 fast_evaluate:            1409 ns/pt
  SVDSBTL+HEOS  (manual loop):    503 ns/pt
  SVDSBTL+IF97  (manual loop):    225 ns/pt

Adding fast_evaluate to SVDSBTL would put it on the same measurement footing as IF97 and is expected to drop these by a meaningful fraction (the AbstractState update() path is ~1-2 us of bookkeeping on top of the actual SVD evaluation).

Implementation sketch (one function override in SVDSBTLBackend):

```cpp
void SVDSBTLBackend::fast_evaluate(
    CoolProp::input_pairs input_pair,
    const double* val1, const double* val2, std::size_t N_inputs,
    const CoolProp::parameters* outputs, std::size_t N_outputs,
    double* out_buffer, std::size_t out_buffer_size,
    int* status_flags, std::size_t status_flags_size,
    CoolProp::phases imposed_phase) override
{
    // Validate buffer sizes (mirror IF97Backend's checks).
    // For each input point k:
    //   1. (a, b) = (val1[k], val2[k]) — adjusted per input_pair
    //   2. Critical-patch check (same predicate as in update()'s routing
    //      branch).  If hit, fall back to patch_source->update() +
    //      read property (this DOES touch a cache, but on a separate
    //      AbstractState instance; cost is still better than ours
    //      doing the bookkeeping every call).
    //   3. Otherwise: surface->evaluate(active_in_patch ? ... )
    //      for each requested output, writing directly to
    //      out_buffer[k * N_outputs + o].
    //   4. Set status_flags[k] = 0 on success, nonzero on per-point
    //      failure (NaN-fill the row).
    // Zero allocations, no touching of this->_T/_p/_cached_* etc.
}
```

Critical-patch routing: the existing patch_source_ AbstractState is owned by the SVDSBTL backend and survives across fast_evaluate calls, so we can reuse it directly.  No need to instantiate it per call.

**Out of scope:**
  * Don't try to vectorize the SVD evaluation kernel itself — that's a separate optimization.  This is purely about removing per-call cache bookkeeping.
  * Don't try to batch the patch-source HEOS calls — they're already
    rare in normal workloads.

**Tests:**
  * Extend src/Tests/CoolProp-Tests-SVDSBTL.cpp with a fast_evaluate
    smoke test that builds a 100-point batch, calls fast_evaluate, and
    asserts the same values as N back-to-back update() + keyed_output()
    calls (bit-identical for in-domain points; both NaN for out-of-domain).

**Profiling validation:**
  * Web/scripts/fluid_properties.IF97Profile.py automatically picks up
    fast_evaluate when available (see existing time_fast_evaluate
    branch).  Re-run after landing to confirm SVDSBTL drops below
    the manual-loop floor.

Parent: foi.10 docs/perf umbrella.

src/Configuration.cpp:~68 lazy-inits the global Configuration singleton:

  static std::unique_ptr<Configuration> pconfig;
  Configuration* _get_config() {
      if (!pconfig) pconfig = std::make_unique<Configuration>();
      return pconfig.get();
  }

PR #2800 protected the FluidLibrary, IncompressibleLibrary, and Cubics/PCSAFT singletons but missed Configuration. Two threads first-calling set_config_bool() / get_config_bool() concurrently both observe pconfig empty, both construct, last assignment wins, first instance leaks; subsequent state depends on whichever thread won. Fix: wrap with std::call_once + std::once_flag (matching FluidLibrary pattern), or convert to a Meyers function-local static singleton.
